  "why": "DistXplore is designed to produce realistic, valid inputs (naturalness) and enforces validity constraints (Lp-based validity and conservative mutation bounds) and validates high validity rates via a manual study. However, the paper does not describe mechanisms that prevent cumulative drift across many iterative mutations by constraining similarity to the original seed (e.g., fixing semantically critical content or measuring similarity relative to the original seed across iterations). Instead, it applies conservative per-mutation constraints and per-iteration GA operations, which enforces plausibility primarily between successive mutation steps but does not explicitly account for compounded distortion over many iterations. Semantic-consistency (preserving the original seed label) is not required by DistXplore (it deliberately moves inputs toward other-class distributions), so only naturalness is applicable and is enforced between successive steps — corresponding to the “Medium” rating.",
